## Accessibility Requirements (WCAG 2.1 Level AA)

**ALL pages on the site MUST meet WCAG 2.1 Level AA accessibility standards.** This ensures the site is usable by people with disabilities and improves SEO.

### 1. Skip Links (Required)

Every page MUST include a skip link immediately after the `<body>` tag:

```html
<body>
    <a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>
    <!-- Rest of content -->
</body>
```

- Skip links allow keyboard users to bypass navigation and jump directly to main content
- The skip link is visually hidden but appears on keyboard focus
- Must target `#main-content` (the main landmark id)
- Styled in `blog-styles.css` and `styles.css` with proper focus states

### 2. Main Content Landmarks (Required)

All pages MUST have a properly identified main content area:

**For blog posts:**
- The React-rendered `<main>` element MUST have `id="main-content"`
- Example: `React.createElement('main', { id: 'main-content' }, ...)`
- This applies to both loading and rendered states

**For index.html and blog.html:**
- Main content area must have `id="main-content"`
- Example: `<main id="main-content">` or `React.createElement('main', { id: 'main-content' }, ...)`

### 3. Semantic HTML Structure

Use proper semantic HTML elements:
- `<nav>` for navigation (with `role="navigation"` and `aria-label="Main navigation"`)
- `<main>` for main content (with `id="main-content"`)
- `<footer>` for footer (with `role="contentinfo"`)
- `<article>` for blog post content
- `<section>` for distinct content sections
- Proper heading hierarchy: `<h1>` ‚Üí `<h2>` ‚Üí `<h3>` (never skip levels)

### 4. ARIA Labels and Roles

**Navigation:**
- Navigation must have: `role="navigation"` and `aria-label="Main navigation"`
- Mobile menu toggle must have:
  - `aria-label="Toggle menu"`
  - `aria-expanded` (dynamically updated: `true`/`false`)
  - `aria-controls="main-navigation"`
- Navigation links should have `role="menuitem"` when in a menu context

**Buttons:**
- All buttons MUST have descriptive `aria-label` attributes
- Icon-only buttons MUST have `aria-label` (never rely on icon alone)
- Example: `<button aria-label="Previous image">‚Äπ</button>`
- Decorative icons inside buttons should have `aria-hidden="true"`

**Interactive Elements:**
- Links that open in new tabs: `aria-label="[Description] - opens in new tab"`
- Image carousels/slideshows: `role="region"`, `aria-label="[Description]"`, `aria-live="polite"`
- Filter buttons: `aria-label="Filter by [category]"`, `aria-pressed="true/false"`

**Decorative Elements:**
- Purely decorative icons/images: `aria-hidden="true"`
- Example: `<span aria-hidden="true">‚úì</span>`

### 5. Images and Alt Text (Required)

**ALL images MUST have descriptive alt text:**

```html
<!-- Good: Descriptive alt text -->
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Mid-century modern living room in Corydon Cute & Stylish Airbnb Winnipeg" loading="lazy">

<!-- Good: Decorative image (use empty alt) -->
<img src="decoration.jpg" alt="" role="presentation">

<!-- Bad: Missing alt text -->
<img src="image.jpg">
```

**Guidelines:**
- Alt text should be descriptive and contextual
- For hero images: Describe the scene/subject
- For content images: Describe what's shown and why it's relevant
- For decorative images: Use `alt=""` and optionally `role="presentation"`
- Never use "image of" or "picture of" - be direct
- Keep alt text concise (typically under 125 characters)

**React Components:**
- Dynamic images in React components should use a function like `getImageAltText(index, total)` to generate descriptive alt text
- All `<img>` elements in React must include `alt` prop

### 6. Keyboard Navigation

**All interactive elements MUST be keyboard accessible:**
- All links and buttons must be focusable with Tab key
- Focus order must be logical (top to bottom, left to right)
- Focus indicators must be visible (defined in CSS with `:focus` and `:focus-visible`)
- Skip links must work with keyboard navigation
- Mobile menu must close on Escape key press

**Focus Styles:**
- Defined in CSS using `--focus-outline` and `--focus-outline-offset` variables
- Must be visible and have sufficient contrast
- Use `:focus-visible` to show focus only for keyboard users (not mouse clicks)

### 7. Heading Hierarchy

**Proper heading structure is REQUIRED:**
- Use `<h1>` only once per page (main page title)
- Use `<h2>` for major sections
- Use `<h3>` for subsections within h2 sections
- Never skip heading levels (e.g., don't go from h1 to h3)
- Headings should be descriptive and meaningful (not just for styling)

**Example structure:**
```html
<h1>Page Title</h1>
  <h2>Major Section</h2>
    <h3>Subsection</h3>
  <h2>Another Major Section</h2>
```

### 8. Form Accessibility (When Forms Are Added)

If forms are added to the site:
- All inputs MUST have associated `<label>` elements
- Use `for` attribute on labels matching input `id`
- Or use `<label>` wrapping the input
- Required fields must be clearly indicated (visually and with `aria-required="true"`)
- Error messages must be associated with inputs using `aria-describedby`
- Form validation errors must be announced to screen readers

### 9. Color Contrast

**Text must meet WCAG AA contrast ratios:**
- Normal text (under 18pt/24px): 4.5:1 contrast ratio
- Large text (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold): 3:1 contrast ratio
- Interactive elements (links, buttons): 4.5:1 contrast ratio
- Focus indicators: Must be clearly visible

**Testing:**
- Use browser DevTools or tools like WebAIM Contrast Checker
- Test with various color vision deficiencies
- Ensure information isn't conveyed by color alone

### 10. Language Attributes

**All pages MUST specify language:**
```html
<html lang="en-CA">
```
- Helps screen readers pronounce content correctly
- Required for proper semantic HTML

### 11. Screen Reader Considerations

**Content must be accessible to screen readers:**
- Use semantic HTML (not just divs with classes)
- Provide text alternatives for all images
- Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible
- Use ARIA labels when semantic HTML isn't sufficient
- Test with screen readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)

**Common Issues to Avoid:**
- Don't use `<div>` or `<span>` for buttons - use `<button>`
- Don't use empty links (`<a href="#">`) - use buttons instead
- Don't hide content with `display: none` if it should be accessible
- Use `visually-hidden` class for screen-reader-only content

### 12. React Component Accessibility

**When creating React components:**
- All interactive elements must have proper ARIA attributes
- Use `React.createElement` with proper props for accessibility
- Ensure keyboard event handlers (onKeyDown, onKeyPress) when needed
- Maintain focus management (e.g., trap focus in modals)
- Update ARIA states dynamically (e.g., `aria-expanded` for menus)

**Example:**
```javascript
React.createElement('button', {
    'aria-label': 'Toggle menu',
    'aria-expanded': isOpen,
    'aria-controls': 'main-navigation',
    onClick: toggleMenu
}, 'Menu')
```

### 13. Testing Checklist

Before publishing any page, verify:
- [ ] Skip link is present and functional
- [ ] Main content has `id="main-content"`
- [ ] All images have descriptive alt text
- [ ] All buttons have aria-labels
- [ ] Navigation has proper ARIA attributes
- [ ] Heading hierarchy is correct (h1 ‚Üí h2 ‚Üí h3)
- [ ] Keyboard navigation works (Tab through all interactive elements)
- [ ] Focus indicators are visible
- [ ] Color contrast meets WCAG AA standards
- [ ] Page has `lang="en-CA"` attribute
- [ ] Test with screen reader (optional but recommended)

